import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="How We Research"
  description="Our sourcing standards: how researched entries are compiled and cross-checked, and what the firsthand label actually means."
>
  <div class="wrap page-body">
    <p class="kicker" style="margin-top: 2rem;">Sourcing standards</p>
    <h1>How We Research</h1>

    <p>
      Let's be upfront: this is not a repair workshop, and we're not professional bench
      engineers. ToolFaultFinder is a research project — we dig into specific tool faults
      and write up what the evidence actually supports, properly sourced. Every entry is
      labelled with one of two source types on its quick-facts plate, so you always know
      exactly what you're reading.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="tag tag-researched">researched</span>&ensp;Compiled from sources — most of the site</h2>
    <p>
      A researched entry means we haven't experienced that fault ourselves. We've compiled
      and cross-checked information from service manuals, manufacturer documentation, repair
      forums, and teardown videos. Researched entries always list their sources in the
      quick-facts plate, and we only publish when multiple independent sources agree on the
      diagnosis. Where sources disagree, we say so rather than picking a side quietly.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="tag tag-firsthand">firsthand</span>&ensp;It happened to our own kit</h2>
    <p>
      A firsthand entry means the fault occurred on a tool we actually own and use, and the
      account describes what we personally saw, tried, and what resolved it. These will
      always be the minority of entries — we document faults as they happen to us, not on
      demand. The value of the label is honesty in both directions: firsthand entries carry
      the weight of direct observation, and everything else doesn't pretend to.
    </p>

    <h2>What we won't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Publish a researched entry based on a single forum post or a single video.</li>
      <li>Present researched content as firsthand experience — the label is the whole point.</li>
      <li>Recommend bypassing safety interlocks, guards, or thermal protection — ever.</li>
      <li>Pad entries with generic advice to hit a word count.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If you've dealt with the same fault and found something different, we want to hear it —
      especially from people with real bench experience. Send details via the
      <a href="/contact/">contact form</a>. Reader corrections are how researched entries get
      improved or fixed, and we'd rather amend an entry than leave it confidently wrong.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
